      "contentSections": [],
      "faqs": [
        {
          "question": "Can my parent keep their house and still qualify for SNAP?",
          "answer": "Yes, the primary home is exempt from asset limits regardless of value. Retirement accounts like 401(k)s and IRAs are also typically exempt for seniors. Only countable assets like bank accounts and investments are considered in the asset test."
        },
        {
          "question": "What if my parent's Social Security is slightly over the income limit?",
          "answer": "Seniors 60+ can still qualify through the net income test even if gross income is too high. Medical expenses, shelter costs, and utility allowances are deducted from gross income — these deductions are often substantial enough for seniors to qualify."
        },
        {
          "question": "Can I apply for SNAP on behalf of my elderly parent?",
          "answer": "Yes, family members can apply as an authorized representative. You'll need to complete additional paperwork showing you have permission to act on their behalf. Call (877) 382-2363 to get the representative designation forms."
        },
        {
          "question": "How much will my parent actually receive each month?",
          "answer": "Benefits depend on net income after deductions. Massachusetts seniors average $147 monthly, but a two-person household could receive up to $546 monthly. The formula is maximum allotment minus 30% of net income, with higher medical and shelter deductions for seniors."
        },
        {
          "question": "Does my parent's pension count as income for SNAP?",
          "answer": "Yes, Social Security, pensions, and disability benefits all count as income. However, seniors get enhanced deductions for medical expenses (including Medicare premiums) and shelter costs that younger applicants don't receive, which often offset higher fixed incomes."
        },
        {
          "question": "Can my parent apply for SNAP and LIHEAP at the same time?",
          "answer": "Yes, and receiving LIHEAP heating assistance actually helps with SNAP — it provides an automatic utility deduction that can increase SNAP benefits. Many seniors qualify for both programs simultaneously."
        },
        {
          "question": "What happens if my parent's medical expenses increase after they're approved?",
          "answer": "Seniors can report changes in medical expenses anytime during their benefit period to request a benefit increase. This includes new prescription costs, medical equipment, or increased insurance premiums. Call the DTA customer service line to report changes."
        },
        {
          "question": "How long do SNAP benefits last for seniors?",
          "answer": "Seniors using the simplified EDSAP application get 36-month benefit periods with no recertification interview required. Regular SNAP recipients typically recertify every 12 months, but the process is streamlined for elderly households."
        }
      ],
