      "faqs": [
        {
          "question": "What if my parent's landlord won't sign the permission forms?",
          "answer": "The landlord must sign agreements not to raise rent for 1 year and not to evict except for good cause. If they refuse, your parent cannot receive weatherization services. Some landlords are more willing when they understand the improvements increase property value at no cost to them."
        },
        {
          "question": "Can my parent apply if they received weatherization help from their utility company?",
          "answer": "Yes, the program coordinates with utility programs like MassSave and won't duplicate services already provided. However, if your parent already received comprehensive weatherization through this specific program before, they're not eligible again."
        },
        {
          "question": "How long is the actual waitlist after approval?",
          "answer": "Processing time varies significantly by region and funding availability. Priority households (elderly, disabled, families with young children) get served first, but even priority cases may wait months depending on local demand and contractor availability."
        },
        {
          "question": "What exactly gets done to the house?",
          "answer": "Services include air sealing, attic/wall/floor insulation, pipe and duct insulation, weather-stripping, heating system tune-ups and repairs, and safety testing of combustion appliances. The specific work depends on your parent's home energy audit results."
        },
        {
          "question": "Can I apply on behalf of my elderly parent?",
          "answer": "You can help with the application process, but your parent typically needs to be involved since they must sign forms as the homeowner or tenant. Contact your local energy assistance agency to discuss specific accommodation needs for elderly applicants."
        },
        {
          "question": "What if my parent's income is slightly over the LIHEAP limits?",
          "answer": "Income limits are based on 60% of state median income or 200% of federal poverty level, whichever is higher. These limits vary by household size and are updated annually. If your parent is over the limit, they won't qualify for this program but may qualify for utility company programs."
        },
        {
          "question": "Does my parent have to pay anything upfront or get reimbursed later?",
          "answer": "No. This is completely free with no upfront costs, co-pays, or reimbursement process. All materials, labor, and inspections are covered by the program at no cost to your parent."
        },
        {
          "question": "What happens if we miss the October 1 to April 30 application window?",
          "answer": "You must wait until the next program year starting October 1. There are no exceptions to this application period, so mark your calendar and apply early in the season to improve chances of getting served that year."
        }
      ],
