      "faqs": [
        {
          "question": "Can my parent get meals if they're not homebound all the time?",
          "answer": "Your parent must be chronically or temporarily homebound and unable to shop or prepare meals. Temporary homebound status — like recovery from surgery or a fall — may qualify. Contact your local provider to discuss your parent's specific situation and mobility limitations."
        },
        {
          "question": "What if my parent lives in an assisted living facility?",
          "answer": "Most Meals on Wheels programs serve people in their own homes or apartments, not assisted living facilities that provide meals. However, some providers may serve seniors in independent living communities. Call your local provider to ask about their specific service area policies."
        },
        {
          "question": "How much will my parent have to pay for meals?",
          "answer": "Most Massachusetts providers offer free meals regardless of income. Some apply means-testing and may charge reduced fees based on ability to pay, but no one is denied meals due to inability to pay. Ask your local provider about their fee structure when you apply."
        },
        {
          "question": "Can I apply on behalf of my parent who has dementia?",
          "answer": "Yes, family members can apply on behalf of a parent who cannot manage their own affairs. You may need to provide documentation of your authority to act on their behalf, such as power of attorney or guardianship papers, depending on your local provider's requirements."
        },
        {
          "question": "What happens on weekends and holidays when meals aren't delivered?",
          "answer": "Most Meals on Wheels programs deliver Monday through Friday only, with no weekend or holiday service. Some providers may offer frozen meals for weekends or connect your parent to other food resources. Ask your local provider about weekend meal options when you apply."
        },
        {
          "question": "How long is the waitlist in my area?",
          "answer": "Wait times vary significantly by region — some areas have immediate availability while others have waitlists due to high demand. Contact your local provider directly for current wait times in your parent's service area. Priority may be given to those with the greatest need."
        },
        {
          "question": "Can my parent get meals if they already receive SNAP benefits?",
          "answer": "Yes, your parent can receive both SNAP benefits and Meals on Wheels — these are separate programs that can complement each other. SNAP helps with groceries while Meals on Wheels provides prepared meals and daily check-ins for homebound seniors."
        },
        {
          "question": "What if my parent's needs change after enrollment?",
          "answer": "Contact your local provider if your parent's condition improves and they no longer need meal delivery, or if their dietary needs change. Most programs can modify special diets or pause service temporarily if your parent is hospitalized or traveling."
        }
      ],
