      "intro": "If your parent is 55+ and unemployed with low income, the Senior Community Service Employment Program (SCSEP) provides paid training positions at nonprofits and public agencies like schools, hospitals, and senior centers. Your parent earns Massachusetts minimum wage for up to 20 hours per week while gaining job skills and work experience.\n\nBecause SCSEP combines immediate income with job placement services, participants work toward unsubsidized employment while earning a paycheck. The program lasts up to 48 months and includes on-the-job training at community organizations. Priority goes to veterans, people over 65, and those with disabilities, limited English, or low employment prospects.\n\nMassachusetts serves all counties through regional providers, but there's no single statewide application. Income must be at or below 125% of the federal poverty level for your parent's household size, and they must be actively seeking permanent employment.",
