      "intro": "If your parent owns their home and needs accessibility modifications like ramps, grab bars, or bathroom adaptations, Massachusetts offers 0% interest loans up to $50,000. Because these are deferred loans, your parent makes no monthly payments — the loan is only repaid when the house is sold, refinanced, or transferred.\n\nThis program specifically covers accessibility modifications tied to documented disabilities or functional limitations. Your parent must be 60+ or have a documented disability, own their home in Massachusetts, and have household income up to 200% of Area Median Income (varies by region, roughly $70,000-$120,000 annually depending on household size and location). Assets cannot exceed $75,000 (excluding their home, one car, and retirement accounts).\n\nThe loan covers ramps, lifts, bathroom modifications, kitchen adaptations, doorway widening, handrails, accessible flooring, and even accessory dwelling units. It does not cover general home repairs like roofing, windows, heating systems, or septic work.",
